items.title: Caladenia pusilla
items.content_text: Tiny plant. Hardly visible it is so small.

items.title: Senecio pinnatifolius var. lanceolatus, Syrphidae spp.
Podargus strigoides
items.content_text: Flying back and forth towards the windows, chasing Rain Moths (Hepialidae).

items.title: Argynnina cyrila
items.content_text: Found floating in a bird bath. Later recovered.

items.title: Belenois java teutonia

items.title: Vanessa itea
items.content_text: Feeding on a garden-planted Pimelea nivea.

items.title: Delias aganippe
items.content_text: Found near a population of Exocarpos cupressiformis.

items.title: Delias harpalyce
items.content_text:
Feeding on a garden-planted Banksia integrifolia.
Food plant likely to be Amyema pendula locally but not confirmed.

items.title: Alternanthera denticulata s.l., Alternanthera denticulata s.s.
Oxalis exilis
items.content_text: Hairs on lowest branches (not stems leading to leaves or flowers) are mostly antrorse/appressed (ie. forwards/upwards against stem) - this is true for O.exilis and O.perennans.

items.title: Arthropodium sp. 3 (aff. strictum)
items.content_text: Suspect this is A. sp. 3. Anthers lack yellow appendages and I can see at least one node with two flowers.

items.title: Geranium sp. 3
items.content_text: Three pics showing 1) flower and spring-summer leaf, 2) close-up of spring-summer leaf with narrow lobes, 3) close-up of over-wintering leaf with broad lobes. In Spring, both leaf-types are seen.

items.title: Pellaea falcata s.l., Pellaea falcata s.s.
Convolvulus angustissimus subsp. omnigracilis
items.content_text: Fruiting pedicel is distictly recurved, which rules out C. remotus. 2nd pic indicates possibly subsp. angustissimus with its broad lower cauline leaves but the higher leaves mean it is probably omnigracilis.
